● This is a config change on the VM, not in the repo. Here's exactly what to run:

  1. Create/edit /etc/docker/daemon.json on the VM:

  sudo tee /etc/docker/daemon.json > /dev/null <<'EOF'
  {
    "default-address-pools": [
      {"base": "192.168.128.0/17", "size": 24}
    ],
    "bip": "192.168.127.1/24"
  }
  EOF

  - default-address-pools — all new compose project networks get addresses from 192.168.128.x – 192.168.255.x, far away
  from your 172.16.0.x host network
  - bip — the docker0 bridge itself (the daemon's default bridge) gets 192.168.127.1/24
  - /17 base with /24 size gives Docker 128 possible team networks — plenty

  2. Purge all existing stale networks (from step before):

  docker network ls --filter 'name=ctf_' --format '{{.ID}}' \
    | xargs -r docker network rm 2>/dev/null || true

  3. Restart Docker:

  sudo systemctl restart docker

  4. Verify the new bridge range:

  docker network inspect bridge | grep Subnet
  # Should show: 192.168.127.0/24

  ip addr show docker0
  # Should show: 192.168.127.1/24

  5. Confirm host route table looks clean:

  ip route show | grep '172.16'
  # Should only show your VM's own NIC route, nothing from Docker

  After this, spawn a test team container and confirm ip route show still only has the one 172.16.0.x route for the host
   NIC.
